"What will happen when people

00:00:30.669 --> 00:00:33.310
spend more time in virtual worlds,
than the real world?"

00:00:34.306 --> 00:00:37.494
A lot of people get worried
about virtual worlds,

00:00:37.494 --> 00:00:40.067
and I think that's where this question
comes from,

00:00:40.067 --> 00:00:42.438
taking our time away
from the real world.

00:00:42.438 --> 00:00:45.475
But, actually, I think, as virtual worlds
become bigger

00:00:45.475 --> 00:00:47.405
and more complex
than the real world,

00:00:47.405 --> 00:00:49.011
it will almost be the opposite.

00:00:49.011 --> 00:00:51.418
We'll worry if people are spending
too much time

00:00:51.418 --> 00:00:54.433
locked into just the place
where they live in the real world,

00:00:54.433 --> 00:00:57.210
where they might only have a limited
set of friends,

00:00:57.210 --> 00:00:59.011
or they might have less diversity
around them

00:00:59.011 --> 00:01:01.112
that they can find
in the virtual worlds.

00:01:01.112 --> 00:01:05.043
So, as virtual worlds replicate
everything we can do

00:01:05.043 --> 00:01:08.172
in the real world, which they will,
I think we are going to see them

00:01:08.172 --> 00:01:11.271
as...a place where...like school.
We want to make sure

00:01:11.271 --> 00:01:13.180
we actually spend enough time in.

00:01:14.036 --> 00:01:16.271
As a matter of fact, there have been
a lot of studies

00:01:16.271 --> 00:01:17.442
even before VR,

00:01:19.621 --> 00:01:22.608
that suggest that people
we see everyday,

00:01:22.608 --> 00:01:24.804
because we've learnt
about them online,

00:01:24.804 --> 00:01:28.693
people we've come to know on-line,
are people that we are far less likely

00:01:28.693 --> 00:01:30.885
to engage in conflict or wars with.

00:01:30.885 --> 00:01:35.302
The more VR becomes a literal world
that you can walk around in,

00:01:35.302 --> 00:01:38.391
a real, physical world like this one,
that feels the same,

00:01:38.391 --> 00:01:41.820
the less likely we are all going to be
to fight with each other.

